(270, 1, '2010-09-06 19:20:12', '2010-09-06 17:20:12', '<h2>North Korea</h2>\r\nOn 26 March 2010, South Korean naval ship has been sunk by the borders of the North Korea.\r\n\r\nToday, South Korea claims to have proof that verifies that the torpedo sinking this ship has been\r\n\r\nfired by the northern neighbor, North Korea, which denies the guilt. The response to accusations\r\n\r\nwas serious, North Korea severed all bonds with South Korea, forbidding any South Korean ship or\r\n\r\nplane to be present on their territory.\r\n\r\nThis restriction goes straight against the Resolution 1874 adopted by United Nations, which\r\n\r\nencourages the inspection and seizure of cargo suspected of being connected to nuclear weapons\r\n\r\ndevelopment because of North Korea''s refusal of disarmament. On top of that, the situation is\r\n\r\nbecoming acute, as can be seen from reactions of both parties in this conflict and the significantly\r\n\r\npowerful and important former ally of North Korea, China. China claims to make reasonable\r\n\r\ndecision about the situation - on which side to stand - on its own, not willing to disrupt peace, but\r\n\r\nnot stating the side which they would stand by in case of an open conflict. Therefore they are not\r\n\r\nexplicitly denying the possibility of sticking with North Korea. Hence, it is not unlikely that an\r\n\r\narmed conflict will break out and as the UN is not able to monitor the arsenal situation in North\r\n\r\nKorea, when taken to further extent, the possibility of second Korean War such as the conflict in\r\n\r\n50''s may be relevant, affecting the lives of millions.\r\n\r\nHence the reason why UN SC should intervene. The question is how. Should they lift the sanctions,\r\n\r\ntighten them up or leave the sanctions as they are? Or should the UN solve this problem in a\r\n\r\ndifferent way?\r\n\r\n<strong>Jakub Páleník</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Download the Study Guide</strong>', 'Security Council', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '180-revision-7', '', '', '2010-09-06 19:20:12', '2010-09-06 17:20:12', '', 180, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(120, 1, '2010-07-08 23:13:27', '2010-07-08 21:13:27', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The BratMUN conference, much like other MUNs, is a  simulation of a real <a href="../wp-content/uploads/2010/06/conference1.png"><img class="alignright" style="margin: 15px 0pt 15px 15px; float: right;" title="At the General Assembly" src="../wp-content/uploads/2010/06/conference1-200x300.png" alt="At the General Assembly" width="200" height="300" /></a>United Nations conference, and so it also proceeds in the same spirit. The conference starts with the opening  ceremony, continues with debates in a number of committees and ends with  a discussion in the General Assembly.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The delegates are required to make research on their countries'' standpoint on issuess discussed in the committees, as th<img alt="" />ey  will be representing their interests. They should have a good insight  into the topics being discussed, so they can provide valuable opinions  and do their best for the country they are representing.</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">After  the discussion in General Assembly, a resolution is issued. The  resolution should be a consensus of the partaking countries on the  topics discussed. After making a resolutions, it is decided whether it  will be accepted or not by voting.</p>', 'What''s MUN?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '23-autosave', '', '', '2010-07-08 23:13:27', '2010-07-08 21:13:27', '', 23, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(93, 1, '2010-06-21 21:35:55', '2010-06-21 19:35:55', '<h2><strong>Traveling to Bratislava</strong></h2>\nThe possibilities of getting to Bratislava include almost all common means of transportation. All stations and airports are highlighted on a map below.\n\n<strong>Traveling by plane</strong>\n\nThere are two airports you can fly to when traveling to Bratislava, the Bratislava airport (<em>BTS</em>) and the Vienna airport - Schwechat (<em>VIE</em>).\n\nThe airport in Bratislava is situated just outside the city itself and is connected with the public transportation system in Bratislava by two bus lines.  (see <em>Traveling around Bratislava</em>)\n\nSchwechat is located in Austria, around 70 km far from the center of Bratislava. When flying to Schwechat, you can get to Bratislava by a bus  (consult <a href="http://www.slovaklines.sk/important-information.html" target="_blank">http://www.slovaklines.sk/important-information.html</a> for further information) that departs from Schwechat every 30 minutes. The journey takes approximately one hour.\n\nLow-cost airlines flying to either Schwechat or Bratislava include Ryanair (BTS and VIE), Air Berlin (VIE) and Easy Jet (VIE).\n\n<a href="http://www.airportbratislava.sk/index.aspx?lang=1033" target="_blank">Website of Bratislava airport </a>| <a href="http://www.viennaairport.com/jart/prj3/va/main.jart?rel=en&amp;reserve-mode=active&amp;content-id=1249344074214" target="_blank">Website of Schwechat airport </a>\n\n<strong>Traveling by train</strong>\n\nWhen traveling by train,  be sure to book your ticket to and arrive at Bratislava - Hlavna Stanica (Main Railway Station), which is situated in the city center, easily accessible by various buses, trolleybuses and trams.\n\nShould you happen to arrive at Bratislava - Petržalka, have no worries, there are more than enough bus lines that will easily take you to the center. (see <em>Traveling around Bratislava</em>)\n\n<a href="http://www.zssk.sk/en" target="_blank">Website of Slovak Rail</a>\n\n<strong>Traveling by bus</strong>\n\nYou can without any problems travel to Bratislava by bus or coach as well. The station you will arrive at when traveling by bus is Bratislava - Mlynské Nivy.\n\n<a href="http://www.slovaklines.sk/index_en.html">Website of Slovak Lines</a>\n<h2>Traveling around Bratislava</h2>\n<strong>Public transport</strong>\n\nThe public transportation system in Bratislava comprises a complex system of bus, trolleybus and tram lines. The whole city is divided into three zones, but the fares vary with different zones only when buying prepaid travel passes (1 month, 3 months or 1 year). The public transport tend to be fairly regular and, especially in the city center, go rather often (some lines even as often as every 5 minutes). The basic rule of thumb applied here is as following: The closer to the city center, the more often the buses go.\n\nFares range from € 0.50 for one-ride 15-minutes ticket and € 0.70 for 60-minutes ticket to € 8.00 for 3-days pass and € 12.00 for a one-week pass. These tickets can be bought in every newspaper agent or in ticket machines (yellow boxes of around 1.2 m in height) which are located by lots of bus and tram stops.\n\nThe complete map of Bratislava public transport can be found in the gallery on the bottom of this page.\n\n<strong>Taking a taxi</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong>\n\n<strong>Remember that there will always be a delegation guide assigned to you or your delegation whose responsibility will be to get you on time wherever you need to be (i.e. the hotel or the venue of the conference). Following information are here only should some unforeseen event occur when the delegation guide will not be around.</strong>\n\n<strong>Getting to the hotel</strong>\n\n<strong>Getting to the venue of the conference</strong>\n\n<strong>Getting to the city center</strong>\n\n<strong>Maps</strong>\n\n<img title="gallery link=&quot;file&quot;" src="http://bratmun.sk/wp-includes/js/tinymce/plugins/wpgallery/img/t.gif" alt="" /><img title="gallery link=&quot;file&quot;" src="http://bratmun.sk/wp-includes/js/tinymce/plugins/wpgallery/img/t.gif" alt="" />[gallery link="file"]', 'Transportation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '28-revision-7', '', '', '2010-06-21 21:35:55', '2010-06-21 19:35:55', '', 28, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
