(185, 1, '2010-08-16 17:26:00', '2010-08-16 15:26:00', '<h2>Women rights</h2>\r\n<a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_ECOSOC.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a>\r\n\r\nIn 1979, The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW) was adopted by General Assembly. It consists of 30 articles designed to protect rights of women. States that signed this convention committed themselves to undertake several steps to provide such protection.\r\n\r\nHowever, despite this step against discrimination of woman, there still exist significant cases where these rights are broken. In the 21<sup>st</sup> century women in most countries represent a minority in democratic assemblies. Aspects such as domestic violence or religion prejudices continue destroying women’s freedom.  For instance according to Human rights watch document from June 2009, Saudi officials require women to obtain permission from male guardians to do daily basic actions like travelling, education or receiving medical care. In the same time, this report pointed out situations when husband refuse to sign a divorce or male guardian refuse to give permission for actions like opening bank account.\r\n\r\nMukhtar Mai was raped on orders of a traditional village council in Pakistan. She was one of minority of women that had the courage to testify against her rapists in court. She was then put on “exit control list” that prevents people from leaving the country. She eventually was allowed to leave Pakistan, but only with soldiers “for her own good”.  Mukhtar is only an example of several women and even little girls that have to face daily traditional manners of treating women like rapes or well-known act of stoning mostly present in villages.\r\n\r\nWhat can the UN do to prevent situations like this?\r\n\r\n<strong>Veronika Šípošová</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>', 'Economic and Social Council', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'economic-and-social-council', '', '', '2010-10-16 15:39:48', '2010-10-16 13:39:48', '', 49, 'http://bratmun.sk/?page_id=185', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(186, 1, '2010-08-16 17:25:54', '2010-08-16 15:25:54', '<h2>Women rights</h2>\nIn 1979, The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW) was adopted by General Assembly. It consists of 30 articles designed to protect rights of women. States that signed this convention committed themselves to undertake several steps to provide such protection.\n\nHowever, despite this step against discrimination of woman, there still exist significant cases where these rights are broken. In the 21<sup>st</sup> century women in most countries represent a minority in democratic assemblies. Aspects such as domestic violence or religion prejudices continue destroying women’s freedom.  For instance according to Human rights watch document from June 2009, Saudi officials require women to obtain permission from male guardians to do daily basic actions like travelling, education or receiving medical care. In the same time, this report pointed out situations when husband refuse to sign a divorce or male guardian refuse to give permission for actions like opening bank account.\n\nMukhtar Mai was raped on orders of a traditional village council in Pakistan. She was one of minority of women that had the courage to testify against her rapists in court. She was then put on “exit control list” that prevents people from leaving the country. She eventually was allowed to leave Pakistan, but only with soldiers “for her own good”.  Mukhtar is only an example of several women and even little girls that have to face daily traditional manners of treating women like rapes or well-known act of stoning mostly present in villages.\n\nWhat can the UN do to prevent situations like this?\n\n<strong>Download the Study Guide</strong>\n\n<strong>Veronika Šípošová</strong>', 'Economic and Social Council', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '185-revision', '', '', '2010-08-16 17:25:54', '2010-08-16 15:25:54', '', 185, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(187, 1, '2010-08-16 17:27:47', '2010-08-16 15:27:47', '<h2>Greece</h2>\r\n<a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/EU_Study_Guide.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a>\r\n\r\nDear delegates,\r\n\r\nIt is our pleasure to welcome you in the EU committee. This year, we are dealing with a major financial crisis which has occurred in Greece. Over the past years, Greek government was systematically spending significantly more money than they collected in tax revenues. This set of policies brought the country to an edge of bankruptcy. Although during the 2000s Greek economy was one of the fastest growing in Europe, at present time it has the second highest government deficit in the world, which was estimated to be 13.6% of GDP. The large deficit does not endanger only the local economy, but has international implications as well. A number of European banks purchased government bonds that now cannot be paid back, a fall in volume of trade in south east Europe puts the neighboring states in trouble, and, most importantly, the basic currency – Euro is losing its value due to the instability.\r\n\r\nTherefore, an immediate intervention has to be made. Delegates belonging to the EU committee will be negotiating a solution to the Greek debt crisis in two phases. The first one, taking place in late April of 2010 will consist of presentation of the attitudes, conditions and possible solutions of the delegates regarding the crisis after Greece officially asked the EU for financial help. The aim of the second session on May 2, 2010 will be the actual ratification of the loan to Greece.\r\n\r\nWe hope to see you in one of the most dramatic Committees of this year’s BratMUN!\r\n\r\nBest regards,\r\n\r\n<strong>Andrea Schmidtová and Lucia Tibenská</strong>', 'European Union', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'eu', '', '', '2010-10-02 16:59:20', '2010-10-02 14:59:20', '', 49, 'http://bratmun.sk/?page_id=187', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2010-08-16 17:27:25', '2010-08-16 15:27:25', '<h2>Greece</h2>\nDear delegates,\n\nIt is our pleasure to welcome you in the EU committee. This year, we are dealing with a major financial crisis which has occurred in Greece. Over the past years, Greek government was systematically spending significantly more money than they collected in tax revenues. This set of policies brought the country to an edge of bankruptcy. Although during the 2000s Greek economy was one of the fastest growing in Europe, at present time it has the second highest government deficit in the world, which was estimated to be 13.6% of GDP. The large deficit does not endanger only the local economy, but has international implications as well. A number of European banks purchased government bonds that now cannot be paid back, a fall in volume of trade in south east Europe puts the neighboring states in trouble, and, most importantly, the basic currency – Euro is losing its value due to the instability.\n\nTherefore, an immediate intervention has to be made. Delegates belonging to the EU committee will be negotiating a solution to the Greek debt crisis in two phases. The first one, taking place in late April of 2010 will consist of presentation of the attitudes, conditions and possible solutions of the delegates regarding the crisis after Greece officially asked the EU for financial help. The aim of the second session on May 2, 2010 will be the actual ratification of the loan to Greece.\n\nWe hope to see you in one of the most dramatic Committees of this year’s BratMUN!\n\nBest regards,\n\nAndrea Schmidtová and Lucia Tibenská', 'World Bank', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '187-revision', '', '', '2010-08-16 17:27:25', '2010-08-16 15:27:25', '', 187, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(189, 1, '2010-08-16 17:28:53', '2010-08-16 15:28:53', '<h2>Haiti</h2>\r\n<strong><a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_WHO.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a></strong>\r\n\r\nWHO is the directing and coordinating authority for health within the United Nations system. It is responsible for providing leadership on global health matters, involving equitable access to essential care and collective defense against transnational threats, monitoring health situation while providing technical support to countries and assessing health trends.\r\n\r\nThere have been many natural disasters in today''s world, including tsunami, floods, hurricanes and earthquakes. In this committee we will focus at the last major natural disaster- 7.0 earthquake that took place at Port-au-Prince, the capital of Haiti, on January 12 of 2010, killed approximately 250,000 people and still continues to give rise to new issues.\r\n\r\nThere are multiple health challenges following Haiti''s earthquake that should be responded to. In the weeks to come, control of communicable diseases will become crucial as Haiti may face outbreaks of diarrheal diseases such as E. coli and cholera due to lack of clean drinking water and health-care options, especially dangerous to infants and young children. Also other threats including health conditions like heart disease, diabetes, and chronic respiratory illness will need to be addressed, along with emotional and mental health issues.\r\n\r\nHaiti needs a hand now – before more lives will be lost. The help from international bodies is desperately needed, because Haiti is not able to cope individually with the consequences after the earthquake since it does not have adequate resources. It is the poorest country in the western hemisphere and one of the poorest countries of the world. Serious plan should be put in place that would prevent mismanaging and misspending money and will benefit the impoverished majority. It should help the country leave its problems behind and improve its current situation, so a new strategy must be developed on how to prevent disease and its spreading. Knowing this, it is the time for the people of the world to unite and make a difference in the lives of those who are suffering, because this is not going to be one of those one-time fix it and forget it events and it will have extended consequences.\r\n\r\n<strong>Martina Mišútová</strong>', 'World Health Organization', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'world-health-organization', '', '', '2010-10-21 10:41:56', '2010-10-21 08:41:56', '', 49, 'http://bratmun.sk/?page_id=189', 0, 'page', '', 0),
