(193, 1, '2010-08-16 17:30:00', '2010-08-16 15:30:00', '<h2>The Democratic Republic of Congo refugees</h2>\r\nViolent conflict in the Equateur province in Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) forced nearly 200,000 Congolese civilians to flee their homes since October 2009 when the inter-communal clashes began. While MONUC (United Nations Organization Mission in the Democratic Republic of Congo) has been set up to improve the situation in the country itself, there is an urgent need for the UN to address the issues of Congolese refugees now inhabiting the Republic of Congo (ROC) and the Central African Republic (CAR). The areas of displacement are mostly lacking basic services to provide even for its own residents and the influx of civilians from DRC has more than doubled the local population making the humanitarian agencies struggle to fulfil their needs. What is more, the current situation in DRC brings on expectations that refugees would be staying in displacement for at least another year, which means a longer term solution that would ensure better conditions for Congolese civilians in ROC and CAR is needed immediately. What steps should UNHCR take in order to achieve this?\r\n\r\nThe UN Refugee agency was established in 1950 by the United Nations general Assembly with a mandate to co-ordinate international action of protecting refugees and resolving related problems worldwide. Its purpose is to ensure the right to seek asylum and find safe refuge in another State, with the option to return home voluntarily, integrate locally or to resettle in a third country with the aim of respecting ones rights and well-being.\r\n\r\n<strong>Zuzana Trnková</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Download the Study Guide</strong>', 'Refugee Agency (HCR)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '191-revision-2', '', '', '2010-08-16 17:30:00', '2010-08-16 15:30:00', '', 191, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(194, 1, '2010-08-16 17:31:37', '2010-08-16 15:31:37', '<h2>Global Warming</h2>\r\n<a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_SCC.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a>\r\n\r\nGlobal warming is nowadays one of the most debated worldwide issues. It’s a huge problem that affects countries round the world. These countries must make important decisions in order to stop global warming. Past attempts to tackle the problem at Kyoto and in Copenhagen have failed; because resolutions were not supported by all key states involved in this issue and not adequate to mitigate global warming. Therefore the delegates from the countries affected by this issue will meet at BratMUN in a UN Summit on Climate Change. They ought to discuss this topic and find new solutions, which will be supported by all of them.\r\n\r\nWe have to make a new worldwide treaty which will bring effective solutions for adaptation and mitigation of global warming. It should replace all previous treaties and ought to be accepted by all involved countries. Our main aims are devising ways to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, finding ways to deploy climate-friendly technology, and financing adaptation and mitigation measures. We have to make a proposal adequate for all countries that can influence this present and pressing problem. It’s the right time to make big decisions, which can bring us positive results. Our future is in our hands.\r\n\r\n<strong>Dominika Belešová</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>', 'Summit on Climate Change', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'summit-on-climate-change', '', '', '2010-10-18 10:02:20', '2010-10-18 08:02:20', '', 49, 'http://bratmun.sk/?page_id=194', 0, 'page', '', 0),
