(340, 1, '2010-10-16 15:39:33', '2010-10-16 13:39:33', '<h2>Women rights</h2>\r\n<a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_ECOSOC.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a>\r\n\r\nIn 1979, The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW) was adopted by General Assembly. It consists of 30 articles designed to protect rights of women. States that signed this convention committed themselves to undertake several steps to provide such protection.\r\n\r\nHowever, despite this step against discrimination of woman, there still exist significant cases where these rights are broken. In the 21<sup>st</sup> century women in most countries represent a minority in democratic assemblies. Aspects such as domestic violence or religion prejudices continue destroying women’s freedom.  For instance according to Human rights watch document from June 2009, Saudi officials require women to obtain permission from male guardians to do daily basic actions like travelling, education or receiving medical care. In the same time, this report pointed out situations when husband refuse to sign a divorce or male guardian refuse to give permission for actions like opening bank account.\r\n\r\nMukhtar Mai was raped on orders of a traditional village council in Pakistan. She was one of minority of women that had the courage to testify against her rapists in court. She was then put on “exit control list” that prevents people from leaving the country. She eventually was allowed to leave Pakistan, but only with soldiers “for her own good”.  Mukhtar is only an example of several women and even little girls that have to face daily traditional manners of treating women like rapes or well-known act of stoning mostly present in villages.\r\n\r\nWhat can the UN do to prevent situations like this?\r\n\r\n<strong>Veronika Šípošová</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>', 'Economic and Social Council', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '185-autosave', '', '', '2010-10-16 15:39:33', '2010-10-16 13:39:33', '', 185, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(341, 1, '2010-08-16 17:34:08', '2010-08-16 15:34:08', '<h2>Women rights</h2>\r\nIn 1979, The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW) was adopted by General Assembly. It consists of 30 articles designed to protect rights of women. States that signed this convention committed themselves to undertake several steps to provide such protection.\r\n\r\nHowever, despite this step against discrimination of woman, there still exist significant cases where these rights are broken. In the 21<sup>st</sup> century women in most countries represent a minority in democratic assemblies. Aspects such as domestic violence or religion prejudices continue destroying women’s freedom.  For instance according to Human rights watch document from June 2009, Saudi officials require women to obtain permission from male guardians to do daily basic actions like travelling, education or receiving medical care. In the same time, this report pointed out situations when husband refuse to sign a divorce or male guardian refuse to give permission for actions like opening bank account.\r\n\r\nMukhtar Mai was raped on orders of a traditional village council in Pakistan. She was one of minority of women that had the courage to testify against her rapists in court. She was then put on “exit control list” that prevents people from leaving the country. She eventually was allowed to leave Pakistan, but only with soldiers “for her own good”.  Mukhtar is only an example of several women and even little girls that have to face daily traditional manners of treating women like rapes or well-known act of stoning mostly present in villages.\r\n\r\nWhat can the UN do to prevent situations like this?\r\n\r\n<strong>Veronika Šípošová</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Download the Study Guide</strong>', 'Economic and Social Council', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '185-revision-3', '', '', '2010-08-16 17:34:08', '2010-08-16 15:34:08', '', 185, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
