(353, 1, '2010-10-21 10:39:06', '2010-10-21 08:39:06', '<h2>Haiti</h2>\r\n<strong><a href="../wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_WHO.pdf"><strong>Download the Study Guide</strong></a></strong>\r\n\r\nWHO is the directing and coordinating authority for health within the United Nations system. It is responsible for providing leadership on global health matters, involving equitable access to essential care and collective defense against transnational threats, monitoring health situation while providing technical support to countries and assessing health trends.\r\n\r\nThere have been many natural disasters in today''s world, including tsunami, floods, hurricanes and earthquakes. In this committee we will focus at the last major natural disaster- 7.0 earthquake that took place at Port-au-Prince, the capital of Haiti, on January 12 of 2010, killed approximately 250,000 people and still continues to give rise to new issues.\r\n\r\nThere are multiple health challenges following Haiti''s earthquake that should be responded to. In the weeks to come, control of communicable diseases will become crucial as Haiti may face outbreaks of diarrheal diseases such as E. coli and cholera due to lack of clean drinking water and health-care options, especially dangerous to infants and young children. Also other threats including health conditions like heart disease, diabetes, and chronic respiratory illness will need to be addressed, along with emotional and mental health issues.\r\n\r\nHaiti needs a hand now – before more lives will be lost. The help from international bodies is desperately needed, because Haiti is not able to cope individually with the consequences after the earthquake since it does not have adequate resources. It is the poorest country in the western hemisphere and one of the poorest countries of the world. Serious plan should be put in place that would prevent mismanaging and misspending money and will benefit the impoverished majority. It should help the country