(364, 1, '2010-10-25 16:18:05', '2010-10-25 14:18:05', '<h2>Piracy in Somalia</h2>\r\n<strong><a href="http://bratmun.sk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/StudyGuide_GA.pdf">Download the study guide</a></strong>\r\n\r\nForget eye patches, wooden legs and parrots. Modern pirates sail modern ships, they are equipped with firearms and contemporary satellite systems to track down their targets. Off the coast of Somalia, piracy nowadays blossoms extraordinarily. Hundreds of ships are being held hostage in the Indian ocean, and billions of dollars are spent on ransoms and rescue missions every year. Governments and armed forces of nearby countries are basically inept in doing anything about it.\r\n\r\nThe Special Political and Decolonization Committee is committed to sustaining peace in the world, especially in volatile African and Middle-eastern countries such as Israel, Palestine, Sudan or Somalia. Therefore, being pressed for time due to graduating attacks of pirates in Indian ocean, the committee is called to discuss and agree upon these vitally important issues in this problem, bearing in mind the urgency of this situation: Is it a responsibility of United Nations to intervene militarily in order to protect the international trade being constantly threatened by piracy? Should the governments of surrounding countries be authorized to intervene themselves even though the piracy doesn''t take place in their territorial waters?\r\n\r\n<strong>Matúš Lupták</strong>\r\n\r\n', 'General Assembly', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '176-revision-8', '', '', '2010-10-25 16:18:05', '2010-10-25 14:18:05', '', 176, 'http://bratmun.sk/%page%', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
